      <body>
         <listPerson>
            <person sex="1" sameAs="Q3180611">
               <persName>
                  <forename>Johann-Michael</forename>
                  <surname>Wansleben</surname>
               </persName>
               <persName type="alt">Vanslebius</persName>
               <persName type="alt">Wansleb</persName>
               <persName type="alt">Vansleb</persName>
               <occupation type="academic">scholar</occupation>
               <birth when="1635-11-01"/>               
               <death when="1679-06-13"/>
               <faith type="Protestantism"/>
               <faith type="Catholicism"/>
              
               <floruit>
                  <persName ref="PRS10036Wansleb"/> was born the son of a Lutheran pastor and began studying theology, philosophy and Oriental languages at <placeName ref="Q1829">Königsberg</placeName> in <date>1654</date>.
                  He became a student of <persName ref="PRS6378Ludolf"/> and was sent to London to take care of the edition of <persName ref="PRS6378Ludolf"/>'s Lexicon and Grammatica.
                  His cooperation with <persName ref="PRS6378Ludolf"/> continued after his return to Germany and he also copied Gǝʿǝz manuscripts throughout Europe. It was <persName ref="PRS10036Wansleb"/>
                  who started alone the mission to Ethiopia prepared by <persName ref="PRS6378Ludolf"/> and financed by <persName ref="PRS3841ErnstI"/>. In <date>1664</date> he reached
                  <placeName ref="Q79">Egypt</placeName>, where he established links with the Coptic church. For security reasons he refrained from continuing his journey to Ethiopia and instead collected in Egypt information concerning Ethiopia.
                  He was also able to copy Ethiopian manuscripts in <placeName ref="INS0308DQ"/>, which he brought with him back to Europe. He returned to <placeName ref="Q38">Italy</placeName> in <date>1665</date>, staying first in 
                  <placeName ref="Q2044">Florence</placeName> and then in <placeName ref="Q220">Rome</placeName>, where he continued to copy Gǝʿǝz manuscripts. He converted to Catholicism and became a Dominican priest. This conversion put an end to his friendly relation
               with <persName ref="PRS6378Ludolf"/>, who was deeply offended by it. In <date>1671</date>, <persName ref="PRS10036Wansleb"/> moved to Paris and undertook a new mission to the
                  Orient from <date>1671</date> to <date>1676</date>, in which he again only arrived as far as Egypt, visiting and reporting on the <placeName ref="LOC2594Dayral"/>
                  and the monastery of <placeName ref="INS0320DAA">St Anthony</placeName>. Though he shipped during this journey almost 600 manuscripts in various languages to <placeName ref="Q142">France</placeName>, the mission
                  was considered a failure and <persName ref="PRS10036Wansleb"/> lived poorly after his return to <placeName ref="Q90">Paris</placeName> in <date>1677</date>. His most important work, 
                  the Histoire de l'Église d'Alexandrie, was published in <date>1677</date>. Until his death he lived in <placeName ref="Q272084">Bourron</placeName>.</floruit>
            </person>
